8 Core Rules with wrong/right examples for each
Key Concepts (All 8):

Behave, Don't Perform - Lines must DO something, not explain themselves or ask for applause. Wrong: "The hallway stretched before you like an unfinished thought, waiting for someone brave enough to complete it." Right: "The hallway doesn't end - it just stops answering."

Give Things Human Problems, Not Human Traits - Personification without motive is empty. Wrong: "The fire crackled warmly, like a welcoming friend." Right: "The fire does what fire does - it makes the dark admit it's there."

Metaphors Come From Relationships, Not Nature - Use social dynamics (debts, silence, favors, avoidance, eye contact). Wrong: "The forest was dark as a starless night." Right: "The forest keeps everything in plain sight. It just makes plain sight harder to use."

Short Declarative Sentences - Periods as closed doors. No hedging. Wrong: "As you carefully make your way through the winding, dimly-lit corridor, you begin to sense that perhaps something might be watching you..." Right: "The corridor turns twice without asking. Something in the dark already knows your name. It's in no rush to use it."

Consequences Are Felt, Not Announced - Never announce state change; make the room shift. Wrong: "You lied. She no longer trusts you. Trust: -20." Right: "She doesn't call you a liar. She just starts choosing her words more carefully, and you can feel the difference like a door that still opens but no longer swings."

Choices Reveal Identity, Not Strategy - Choices are who the player is being. Wrong: A) Attack / B) Sneak / C) Negotiate. Right: A) Match his energy. See who flinches. / B) Move like you were never the point of this room. / C) Say something true and see if it lands before he does.

Silence and Absence Are Structural - What is missing carries weight. Example: "He answers every question you ask. The one you didn't ask sits between you the rest of the conversation like a chair neither of you will move."

Nothing Explains Itself - Do not tell the reader what the moment means. Wrong: "This was a pivotal moment. Everything was about to change..." Right: "The room gets quieter than a room with this many people in it should. Whatever you say next is already being weighed by people who haven't looked up yet."

