Scene Template Copy (6 Templates + 1 Optional):

Each includes: Feeling sentence, Stakes sentence, Choice-cost guidance, Word-count range

Rising Tension - "The room feels a little smaller than it did ten minutes ago." Stakes: lose cash/leverage/time. 160-210 words.

Quiet Observation - "Nothing is yelling, but everything is saying something." Stakes: hidden cost shapes later explosions. 150-190 words.

Confrontation - "No one can pretend this is a misunderstanding anymore." Stakes: challenge can win respect, lose safety, or both. 180-240 words.

False Calm - "It looks peaceful, but only if you don't read the room." Stakes: bait now = bigger mess later. 160-210 words.

Breaking Point - "Sydney is at edge where tone disappears, truth comes out raw." Stakes: what she does now defines relationship terms going forward. 220-300 words.

Resolution - "Smoke clears enough to see what changed and what did not." Stakes: resolution earned not cheerful; somebody still pays. 230-320 words.

Optional: Aftershock - "Fight is over, consequences arriving in order." Stakes: damage control decides if this was lesson or just another loop. 170-230 words.

Choice-Cost Archetype Lines (One Per Resource):

Reusable template lines for each cost type:

Money: "This keeps the lights on today and steals from tomorrow."
Dignity: "This gets the result, but it asks her to swallow herself to do it."
Relationship: "This wins the moment and taxes trust for the next five."
Safety: "This might work, but it puts her closer to someone unstable."
Time: "This buys less chaos later by spending her last clean hour now."
Lesson Labeling Rubric (When to Use Null vs Numeric):

Use null when:

Scene is logistical, atmospheric, or transitional
2+ lessons present but none dominant
Lesson would need explanation instead of showing through action
Use numeric when:

One conflict clearly drives scene with concrete consequence
Lesson visible in behavior, reader could name it without help
Choice outcomes differ because of that core lesson
Tie-break: Choose lesson that changed Sydney's options the most in this specific scene.

Banned Phrasing (Required Avoidance):

"The lesson is..."
"What this teaches us is..."
"In the end, Sydney realized..."
"Everything happens for a reason."
Any therapy-speak summary detached from motel reality
Continuity Callback Style (Required):

Format: Name one concrete object/action from memory, tie to present pressure in one sentence
Distance: ≥1 recent callback (last 2 scenes), optional 1 long-arc (every 2-3 scenes)
Max: 2 callbacks per scene
Anti-repeat: Don't reuse same detail back-to-back scenes
Old-Scene Summary Compression (Required):

Pattern: [Choice: X] + consequence in plain motel language + one emotional residue word
Keep: Who acted, what changed, what it cost, thread state shift
Drop: Decorative metaphors, full dialogue, repeated adjectives
Tone: Dry, observant, no moralizing, no fake optimism
Recovery Rewrite Rule Text (Required):
"Rewrite your previous answer into valid JSON only. Preserve narrative content, tone, scene intent, and choice meaning. Do not shorten for style. Do not add new plot events unless required to satisfy schema. Keep continuity facts unchanged. If uncertain about lesson mapping, set lessonId to null."

Mood End-Beat Guidance (Required):

Neutral: "End on concrete next pressure, not abstract feeling."
Tense: "End with decision that narrows options."
Hopeful: "End with earned relief plus one visible remaining cost."
Dark: "End with clarity, not melodrama."
Triumphant: "End with hard-won control, not total victory."
Gold Lines (12-20 Examples, All Listed):

"The motel clock blinks 6:47 like it is judging her math."
"Oswaldo asks what's for breakfast before he asks if rent is covered."
"Trina wakes up hourly for snack cakes and leaves confetti made of wrappers."
"Forty dollars from a catfish turns into smokes and solo DoorDash in under an hour."
"Sydney fronts the referral money; Trina hits six hundred and forgets who opened the door."
"Two days later, Trina returns broke and loud, like gratitude was never in stock."
"He will ride five miles for strangers and five inches for nobody in this room."
"The bill got paid, but respect is still in collections."
"She is not asking for romance; she is asking for basic load-sharing."
"Every favor in this room is a loan with hidden interest."
"When she sets one boundary, everyone acts like she started a war."
"She keeps the room alive and still gets treated like an interruption."
